<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="specPoint"><h2 id="t-cell-response">T Cell Response</h2><ul><li><p><b>T cells</b>, sometimes known as T lymphocytes, are a <b>type of white blood cell</b> involved with the specific immune response</p><ul><li><p>They are produced in the bone marrow and finish maturing in the <b>t</b>hymus, which is where the <b>T </b>in their name comes from</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Mature <b>T cells</b> have specific cell surface receptors called <b>T cell receptors</b></p></li><li><p>These receptors have a <b>similar structure to antibodies</b> and are each <b>specific to a particular type of antigen</b></p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="_The maturation of T-lymphocytes" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1218" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/The-maturation-of-T-lymphocytes.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b> Mature T cells have many different types of receptor on the cell surface membrane; these receptors will bind to different antigens on antigen presenting cells</b></i></p><ul><li><p>T cells are <b>activated</b> when they encounter and <b>bind to their specific antigen</b> on the surface of an antigen presenting cell </p><ul><li><p>This <b>antigen-presenting </b>cell might be a <b>macrophage, </b>an <b>infected body cell</b>, or the <b>pathogen</b> itself</p></li></ul></li><li><p>These activated T cells <b>divide</b> <b>by</b> <b>mitosis</b> to increase in number</p><ul><li><p>Dividing by mitosis produces <b>genetically identical cells</b>, or <b>clones</b>, so all of the daughter cells will have the <b>same type of T cell recepto</b>r on their surface </p></li></ul></li><li><p>As they divide by mitosis the T cells <span class="popovers" data-content="The process during development where cells become more specialised as they mature. It is a result of certain genes being expressed." data-title="Differentiation" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">differentiate</span> into <b>three main types </b>of T cell</p><ul><li><p><b>T helper cells</b></p><ul><li><p>Release chemical signalling molecules that help to <b>activate B cells</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>T killer cells</b></p><ul><li><p>Bind to and <b>destroy infected cells</b> displaying the relevant specific antigen</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>T memory cells</b></p><ul><li><p><b>Remain in the blood</b> and enable a faster specific immune response if the same pathogen is encountered again in the future</p></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></div></div></div>